# launchctlHelper

Small Rich-based CLI for inspecting macOS `launchctl` services and the plist files that define them.

## Features

- Scans common launchd plist directories:
  - `/System/Library/LaunchDaemons`
  - `/Library/LaunchDaemons`
  - `/System/Library/LaunchAgents`
  - `/Library/LaunchAgents`
  - `~/Library/LaunchAgents`
- Shows:
  - launchd label
  - inferred domain (`gui/<uid>`, `user/<uid>`, or `system`)
  - plist source path
  - current PID from `launchctl list` when available
  - disabled state from `launchctl print-disabled`
- Supports:
  - `status`
  - `load`
  - `unload`
  - `enable`
  - `disable`
  - `find`
  - `doctor`

## Install

```bash
uv sync
```

The first `uv sync` needs network access so `uv` can resolve and install dependencies.

## Usage

```bash
uv run launchctl-helper list
uv run launchctl-helper list --running
uv run launchctl-helper find postgres
uv run launchctl-helper status homebrew.mxcl.postgresql@16
uv run launchctl-helper status ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.example.agent.plist
uv run launchctl-helper load ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.example.agent.plist --dry-run
uv run launchctl-helper unload com.example.agent --domain gui/$(id -u) --dry-run
uv run launchctl-helper disable com.example.agent --domain gui/$(id -u) --dry-run
uv run launchctl-helper doctor
```

## Notes

- `load` uses `launchctl bootstrap`.
- `unload` uses `launchctl bootout`.
- `status` tries `launchctl print` across `gui/<uid>`, `user/<uid>`, and `system` unless you pass `--domain`.
- Runtime visibility is strongest for the current user session because `launchctl list` is domain/context-sensitive.
- If you manage system daemons, some operations may still require `sudo`.
